// ============================================================
//  INHERITANCE — Interview Cheat Sheet
// ============================================================
//
//  Q: What is Inheritance?
//  A: A mechanism where a child class acquires the fields and
//     methods of a parent class, enabling code reuse and
//     establishing an "is-a" relationship.
//
//  Q: WHY do we need it?
//  A: Two reasons:
//
//     1. CODE REUSE (DRY — Don't Repeat Yourself)
//        → Common fields (name, id) and behavior (checkIn,
//          checkOut) written ONCE in the parent.
//        → 10 employee types? checkIn logic exists in 1 place.
//        → Fix a bug → fixed for all subtypes automatically.
//
//     2. ESTABLISH A TYPE HIERARCHY
//        → FullTimeEmployee IS-A Employee.
//        → This lets you write methods like processPayroll(Employee e)
//          that work with ANY employee type.
//        → Enables polymorphism (next topic!).
//
//  Q: What is "Favor Composition over Inheritance"? ⭐ VERY COMMON
//  A: This means: don't use inheritance just for code reuse.
//     Use it ONLY for genuine "is-a" relationships where ALL
//     parent behavior makes sense for the child.
//
//     BAD EXAMPLE:
//       Employee has checkIn(). FreelanceEmployee extends Employee.
//       But freelancers don't check in! Now you override checkIn()
//       to do nothing. That's a sign inheritance is wrong here.
//
//     GOOD ALTERNATIVE (Composition):
//       Define Attendable interface (checkIn, checkOut).
//       Define Payable interface (calculateSalary).
//       FullTimeEmployee implements BOTH.
//       FreelanceEmployee implements only Payable.
//       Each class picks its capabilities. No unwanted baggage.
//
//  Q: Types of inheritance in Java?
//  A: - Single: A extends B
//     - Multilevel: A extends B, B extends C
//     - Hierarchical: B extends A, C extends A
//     - ❌ Multiple class inheritance NOT allowed in Java
//       (Diamond Problem). Use interfaces instead.
//
//  Q: What is the Diamond Problem?
//  A: If class C extends both A and B, and both A and B have
//     a method doSomething(), which version does C inherit?
//     Java avoids this ambiguity by disallowing multiple class
//     inheritance. Interfaces solve it because:
//     → If two interfaces have same default method, the
//       implementing class MUST override it explicitly.
//
//  Q: When to use Inheritance vs Interface vs Composition?
//  A:
//     INHERITANCE (extends)
//     → True "is-a" relationship
//     → Child needs ALL parent behavior
//     → You want to share implementation, not just contract
//     → Example: ArrayList IS-A AbstractList
//
//     INTERFACE (implements)
//     → "can-do" / capability contract
//     → Unrelated classes share a behavior
//     → Example: both List and Set implement Collection
//
//     COMPOSITION (has-a)
//     → One class USES another class
//     → More flexible, less coupling
//     → Example: Car HAS-A Engine (Car doesn't extend Engine!)
//
//  Q: Can you call parent's constructor from child?
//  A: Yes, using super(). It MUST be the first statement in
//     the child's constructor. If not explicitly called, Java
//     auto-calls the no-arg super().
//
//  Q: Can you prevent a class from being inherited?
//  A: Yes — declare it as "final class". Example: String is final.
//     Can also use final on individual methods to prevent
//     overriding while still allowing class inheritance.
//
// ============================================================
